6.00	Fascial	Fascia	A fascia (plural fasciae ; adjective fascial; from Latin: "band") is a layer of fibrous tissue. A fascia is a structure of connective tissue that surrounds muscles, groups of muscles, blood vessels, and nerves, binding some structures together, while permitting others to slide smoothly over each other. Various kinds of fascia consists of distinct layers, depending on their functions and their anatomical location: a superficial fascia, a deep fascia, and a subserous (or visceral) fascia and extends uninterrupted from the head to the tip of the toes.	http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/2a/Gray395.png/250px-Gray395.png
